                <h1>Backdrop vs Background: Key Differences Explained</h1>
                <p>In visual design, "backdrop" refers to a large, often physical, scene or setting that enhances the overall composition, while "background" usually pertains to the area behind the main subject in an image. Backdrops create depth and context, while backgrounds provide less emphasis but are crucial in establishing mood and environment.</p>
